years <- unique(crime$Year)
for (year in years){
  assign(paste("year_", year, sep = ""),crime[ which(crime$Year==year),])
}

Analyzing the Percentage of crime rate across the areas in the year 2018

library(stringr)

## For Year 2018
count_arr <- table(year_2018$Location.Description, year_2018$Arrest)
count_arr <- as.data.frame(count_arr)
airport<-subset(count_arr,str_detect(count_arr$Var1, "AIRPORT")==TRUE)
street<-subset(count_arr,str_detect(count_arr$Var1, "STREET")==TRUE)
residential <-subset(count_arr,str_detect(count_arr$Var1, "RESIDE")==TRUE)
public <-subset(count_arr,str_detect(count_arr$Var1, "PUBLIC")==TRUE)
school <-subset(count_arr,str_detect(count_arr$Var1, "SCHOOL")==TRUE)
private <-subset(count_arr,str_detect(count_arr$Var1, "PRIVATE")==TRUE)
building <- subset(count_arr,str_detect(count_arr$Var1, "BUILDING")==TRUE)
apartment <- subset(count_arr,str_detect(count_arr$Var1, "APARTMENT")==TRUE)
CTA <- subset(count_arr,str_detect(count_arr$Var1, "CTA")==TRUE)
CHA <- subset(count_arr,str_detect(count_arr$Var1, "CHA")==TRUE)

air_sum <- sum(airport$Freq)/sum(count_arr$Freq)
street_sum <- sum(street$Freq)/sum(count_arr$Freq)
resid <- sum(residential$Freq)/sum(count_arr$Freq)
publ <- sum(public$Freq)/sum(count_arr$Freq)
sch <- sum(school$Freq)/sum(count_arr$Freq)
priv <- sum(private$Freq)/sum(count_arr$Freq)
build <- (sum(building$Freq) +sum(apartment$Freq))/sum(count_arr$Freq)
cta <- sum(CTA$Freq)/sum(count_arr$Freq)
cha <- sum(CHA$Freq)/sum(count_arr$Freq)

area_name = c("Airport","Street", "Residential","School","Public", "Private","Building/Apt","CTA", "CHA")
area_freq = c(air_sum, street_sum, resid, sch, publ,priv,build,cta, cha)

df.crime_area = data.frame(x=area_name, y=area_freq)
ggplot(data=df.crime_area, aes(x,y*100, group=1)) +
  geom_point() + geom_line() + xlab("Area") + ylab("Percentage") + 
  ggtitle("Percentage of Crimes area-wise in 2018")

Oservation: Resedential Area suffers the maximum criminal situations.

The trend remains the same in year 2017 for resedential area Lets analyze the heat-map of resedential area against different types of crime.

df <- crime %>%
  filter(str_detect(Location.Description, "RESIDE")==TRUE) %>%
  group_by(Primary.Type, Year) %>%
  summarise(n = n())
## Warning: package 'bindrcpp' was built under R version 3.4.4
resid_heatmap <- ggplot(df, aes(y=factor(Year),x=Primary.Type, fill=n)) +
  geom_tile(aes(fill=n)) +
  geom_text(aes(label=n), size=4, color="black") +
  scale_x_discrete("Primary Types", expand = c(0,-1)) +
  scale_y_discrete("Year") +
  scale_fill_gradient("Frequency", low = "white", high = "steelblue") +
  ylab("Year") +
  xlab("Primary Types") +
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1)) +
  theme(axis.text=element_text(size=10)) +
  theme(legend.position="none") +
  ggtitle("Crime levels in Residential area by Year\n") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face="bold", size="20"))
resid_heatmap

Battery is the most observed crime type followed by Theft type Similarly, analyzing the building and apartment area

df2 <- crime %>%
  filter(str_detect(Location.Description, "BUILDING")==TRUE) %>%
  group_by(Primary.Type, Year) %>%
  summarise(n = n())

df3 <- crime %>%
  filter(str_detect(Location.Description, "APARTMENT")==TRUE) %>%
  group_by(Primary.Type, Year) %>%
  summarise(n = n())
for (i in 1:ncol(df3)){
  if(df2$Primary.Type[i]==df3$Primary.Type[i] && df2$Year[i]==df3$Year[i]){
    tot <- df2$n[i]+df3$n[i]
    df3$n[i] <- tot
  }
}
  ggplot(df3, aes(y=factor(Year),x=Primary.Type, fill=n)) +
  geom_tile(aes(fill=n)) +
  geom_text(aes(label=n), size=4, color="black") +
  scale_x_discrete("Primary Types", expand = c(0,-1)) +
  scale_y_discrete("Year") +
  scale_fill_gradient("Frequency", low = "white", high = "steelblue") +
  ylab("Year") +
  xlab("Primary Types") +
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1)) +
  theme(axis.text=element_text(size=10)) +
  theme(legend.position="none") +
  ggtitle("Crime levels in Building/Apartment area by Year\n") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face="bold", size="20"))

Developing a model

  library(caret)  
## Warning: package 'caret' was built under R version 3.4.4
## Loading required package: lattice
residential_sub <- subset(crime,str_detect(Location.Description, "RESIDE")==TRUE)
#residential_sub_prim <- table(residential_sub$Primary.Type, residential_sub$Year)
#residential_sub_prim <- as.data.frame(residential_sub_prim)

for(i in 1:ncol(residential_sub)){
  if((str_detect(residential_sub$Primary.Type[i], "BATTERY")==TRUE)
     ||(str_detect(residential_sub$Primary.Type[i], "THEFT")==TRUE)){
    residential_sub$Type[i] <- 0
  }
 else{
    residential_sub$Type[i] <- 1
  }
}

residential_sub$District[is.na(residential_sub$District)] <- 0
residential_sub$Ward[is.na(residential_sub$Ward)] <- 0
residential_sub$Community.Area[is.na(residential_sub$Community.Area)] <- 0

set.seed(3035)
intrain <- createDataPartition(y = residential_sub$Type, p= 0.7, list = FALSE)
training <- residential_sub[intrain,]
testing <- residential_sub[-intrain,]
#anyNA(residential_sub$Year)
trctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10)
set.seed(3235)
